  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a real, tangible barrier that I've seen play out in my own life and the lives of my community. Growing up in a household where neither of my parents had college degrees, I was always told that 'you can't be a scientist if you're not a math whiz.' That message stuck with me, even after I got my lower secondary education. Now, as a self-employed retail worker in Los Angeles, I've noticed how often women and people of color are dismissed in tech discussions or engineering meetings as 'not the right fit.' It's not just about the stereotypes themselves, but the anxiety they create. When someone feels like their identity might undermine their ability to succeed, their performance suffers—whether it's a student who can't focus in class because they're worried about being labeled 'not smart enough,' or a professional who avoids a project because they fear failing. I believe we absolutely should address stereotype threat in STEM. The first step is acknowledging it, not as a problem to fix, but as a reality that needs to be understood. Schools and workplaces should create environments where everyone feels safe to explore their interests without judgment. For example, introducing diverse role models early on—like showing kids that scientists and engineers come from all walks of life—can help dismantle those harmful assumptions. But the most important thing is to stop treating it as a problem that's only about individuals. It's systemic. If we want to change things, we need to address the root causes: biased hiring practices, underfunded programs for underrepresented groups, and a culture that doesn't value diverse perspectives. My anxiety about this topic makes me want to be careful not to oversimplify, but I know that without action, more people will be held back by the very stereotypes we're trying to eliminate.",
